comments.body:
The issue in this particular case was quite surprising: We are sending the user to "/users/somebody@gmail.com" but Rails is interpreting the ".com" as a file extension and splitting the value in the URL into `id=somebody@gmail` and `format=com` and that's what's causing the look up by email "somebody@gmail" to fail. 

I did a quick fix in PR #995 to handle this.
@escowles you were right, that was the issue.

This seems to boot the service:

```bash
root@e6912fa2a153:/setup# /usr/bin/env java -jar /usr/local/mediaflux/bin/aserver.jar application.home=/usr/local/mediaflux nogui
```

...as the HTTP interface will then be bound and available to `localhost:8888`:

```bash
root@e6912fa2a153:/setup# curl -I localhost:8888/
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Connection: Close
Cache-Control: private
Server: Mediaflux
Date: Mon, 20 Feb 2023 14:37:34 +0000
Last-Modified: Thu, 22 Dec 2022 18:41:00 +0000
Content-Length: 523
Content-Type: text/html
x-arc-content-csum: 5481338E
```

User credentials are found within the following file:

```bash
root@e6912fa2a153:/setup/config# head users.json
{
    ":" :[
        {
            "first": "Craig",
            "last": "Vanderborgh",
            "password": $SECRET,
            "email": "craig.vanderborgh@arcitecta.com"
        },
        {
            "first": "Todd",
```

The following is necessary to authenticate using `mfcommand`:

```bash
root@e6912fa2a153:~# cd /setup/scripts/convenience/
root@e6912fa2a153:/setup/scripts/convenience# bash ./mfcommand logon system manager change_me
```

The previous step was necessary in order to ensure that I could then invoke commands:

```bash
root@e6912fa2a153:/setup/scripts/convenience# bash ./mfcommand user.list :domain system
    :user -id "43" -domain "system" -internal "false" -aid "988" "Craig.Vanderborgh"
    :user -id "44" -domain "system" -internal "false" -aid "989" "Todd.Weybrew"
    :user -id "15" -domain "system" -internal "false" -aid "0" "manager"
    :user -id "19" -domain "system" -internal "true" -aid "0" "replicator"
    :user -id "18" -domain "system" -internal "false" -aid "0" "service"
    :complete "true"
```

Invoking the following for `docker` (this should probably be restructured for `docker-compose`), I was able to successfully authenticate using `localhost`:

```bash
docker run \
  --interactive \
  --rm \
  --tty \
  --privileged \
  --init \
  --name mediaflux \
  --publish 0.0.0.0:8888:8888 \
  regdev.rc.princeton.edu/developer-image:latest \
  /bin/bash
```

...then, from within the environment of the Docker container using the terminal session created by the previous invocation:

```bash
root@c981fcd1859c:/setup# /usr/bin/env java -jar /usr/local/mediaflux/bin/aserver.jar application.home=/usr/local/mediaflux nogui
```

I was then able to access this using a web browser for `localhost`:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/220147958-13fadf5a-58d2-4736-ab9b-97bf43806cd9.png)

Please note that I am still struggling to determine how one can authenticate using personal user accounts (e. g. `jrg5@princeton.edu`). Currently I am still relying upon the `manager` user account within the `system` domain.

I have found the solution for this now as well, this became clear within the `aterm`:

```bash
> authentication.domain.list
	:domain -type "local" "mflux"
	:domain -type "local" "princeton.edu"
	:domain -type "local" -description "Default bootstrap domain" "system"
	:domain -type "local" "www-public"
> user.list :domain princeton.edu
	:user -id "51" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "995" "Bess.Sadler"
	:user -id "49" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "993" "Carolyn.Cole"
	:user -id "53" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "997" "Chuck.McCallum"
	:user -id "52" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "996" "Hector.Correa"
	:user -id "50" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "994" "James.Griffin"
	:user -id "46" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "990" "John.Wiggins"
	:user -id "48" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "992" "Kate.Lynch"
	:user -id "47" -domain "princeton.edu" -internal "false" -aid "991" "Rishi.Joshi"
	:complete "true"
```

Using the domain `princeton.edu` and user names which are human-readable (e. g. `James.Griffin`), one can then authenticate. I relied upon retrieving the passwords using a second terminal session and reading the content of the file `/setup/config/users.json`.

comments.body: Made a fresh clean branch, but hit the same error.

Glanced at SO, but no obvious answer.

Between `pdc_describe` and this repo, there are a few differences, but none of these seem like an obvious problem.
- devise has moved from 4.8.1 to 4.9.0
- In `from_cas` missing `if user.nil?` ... but I don't think we're even reaching that point.
- `devise.rb` for pdc_describe is missing `config.responder.error_status` and `config.responder.redirect_status` but otherwise no significant difference.

Next: look at the devise release notes between 4.8.1 and 4.9.0

There have been [some changes](https://github.com/heartcombo/devise/wiki/How-To:-Upgrade-to-Devise-4.9.0-%5BHotwire-Turbo-integration%5D#omniauth-sign-in-links-in-the-shared-views-changed-to-buttons), but it seems to be in what the button does, and I don't think that's our problem. The partial where the error arises hasn't changed between versions:
```
diff ~/.asdf/installs/ruby/3.1.3/lib/ruby/gems/3.1.0/gems/devise-4.9.0/app/views/devise/sessions/new.html.erb \
     ~/.asdf/installs/ruby/3.0.3/lib/ruby/gems/3.0.0/gems/devise-4.8.1/app/views/devise/sessions/new.html.erb
```

But it seems odd that we're even hitting this form -- This is a login form, and it shouldn't be our code or our dependency that is generating the form, I don't think.
